nee. II Ran\nworn Goins and William assius.\nMOLLIE HARRAWAY\nIS DEAD\nMollie Harraway. 49 years old, 336\nRondo avenue, died from a heart at\nta-k September 9 at her home She\nhad Isen a resident of St Paul for\nmore than thirty years and was a\nmember of the Col Charles Young\nAuxiliary.\nSurvivors imlude her husband.\nMack, one grandchild. Pvt. L. Kllro\nwan Harraway, stationed at Camp\nCrowder. Mo. two great grandchil\ndren. Ellrowan Jr and Della I-eora\nThe body was In state at Brooks\nFuneial Home Tuesday and funeral\nservices were held there Wednesday.\nSeptemtier 12, at 2 p m with Rev Jo\nseph Jackson, assistant pastor of St\nJaema A M E. church, officiating, in\nthe absence of Rev B N. Moore.\nBurial was at Oakland ceemtery.\nCredjafawn Credit\nUnion Meets\nThe monthly meepng of the Board\nof Idrectors and officers of the red\njafav n Credit t nlon will meet at the\nhome of Mr and Mrs Huron J She!\nton. Jr. 453 Kent street on Friday\nSeptemlwr 14 at J\" pm with Miwa\nLvdla Jones as hostess\nNEW MAH. St HS< KIBER-S\nl I. Blodgett. 2720 W. tith Si, Mpte. 1(1. Minn.\nGordon V Braun. .1029 hiesgo A\u00bbe\u201e Mplw. Minn\nJack Diamond. 67\u00ab Rondo Avenue. M. Paul I\nMrs Homer Anderson. 711 ayrod Axe.. SI. Paul I\nH. J. Shellon. Reni St.. St. Paul 3\nCo-Op Store No. 3 Has Grand\n\u201cSHORTY\u201d GRAHAM\nIS DEAD\n1 Meredith J Graham, popularly\nknown as Shorty.\" died on Saturday,\nSeptember 8. at 445 Wacouta street,\ni Born in Hot Springs, Arkansas. Sep\ni tember 15, 1892, he had been a rest\nI dent of the city for the past thirty\nseven years.\nSurvivors include two daughters.\nMrs Maurice Boyd and Mrs. Ikirothy\nRoberts, two brothers. Thomas of\nDetroit and Wiley of Kansas City.\nFuneral services were held Wed\nnesday. September 12. at 2 p m. from\nthe Neal Funeral Home. 525 Rondo\navenue, with the Rev. Floyd Massey,\nJr. officiating Burial was In Elm\nhurst cemetery.\nURBAN LEAGUE\nDINNER MEETING\nThe founder* uf the St Paul Urban\nLeague will be honored at the twen\nty Mvond annual mevting on Septum\nber 20. l\u2019.U5. Two prominent buui\nnew men, 8 E Hall and Owen How\nell. Mra .Mary I). McFarland who Is\nwell known for her long period of\nmtvLu in Community Chest and rifle\nla< th Hies, and John .1 Doyle, proba\nHou offi\u00aber of Hamtay County have\nI given many yearn of service and are\nunlinuinK to nerve the I than league.\nThe oim idem of the holding of the\nmeeting in the fellowship hall of the\n'Pilgrim Baptist chur< h Is that when\nthe League wan organised in St Paul,\njibe Hint m toting was held in thia in\ni MHiHion When the Urban League\nwan founded, it wan during a period\nwlitii job op|x>rt unit lea were lhnH<*<l\nfor N\u00abgio citizens Today, we are\nin a similar period when joba are\nJ needed.\nI In tarrying out the polity of ex\npanding Job opportunities M A Cope,\ndire< tor of Industrial Relations for\nShure Bron, Company. Chicago, Illi\nnedn. will la* the principal speaker\nMr Cope in a graduate of the Uni\nversify of ('hhago. He ha* taught at\nthe Illinois Institute of Tim hnology\nand the University of llllnolti For\nseveral yearn he han bten active in the\nIndustrial Relationa Association of\nChi< ago and also with Mayor Kelley s\nCommittee of Race Relations Serving\nmm hairman of the nulk ommiltee on\nI management and minority group rm\nployment Mr. Cope in regarded as an\nexcellent apt akt r ami will have a niw\nave that will Interest the entire com\ntnunity. Hiw aubjeft will Ih What In\nthe ID wponnibility of Management for\nProviding Employment for Minority\nGroup#?\u201d\nReservations will be accepted until\nSepti nil>\u00abr 17 Pr- \u00bbnt lndi< at lons an*\nthat a large numlsi of white and N<\nLio titi/ms will b\u00bb present S|mtlhl\ninvitations have been extended to Gov\nrnor Edward J Thy< Mayor John J\nM< D nough and im inla rM of the city\noumil Many prominent bu^ineMN men\nand industrialists have indicated that\nthey will la- present Th< dinner will\njata** promptly at L\u2019 Tl< ket* are\n11 oO\nNorth Side Church\n.VliMNionary\nI\u2019rebklent KHunw from\nNational Meet\nMrs. Mary Crump, 951 Al- i\ndrich Ave. No., President of\nthe Missionary Society, Zion\nBaptist Church, returned home\nTuesday, Sept. 11. The Women\u2019s\nConvention stressed a more di\nrect approach to the less fortu\nnates in their Post-War pro\ngram in both their Home For\neign Missionary Field. All Mis\nsionary workers were urged to\nexert a stronger influence in\ntheir program of Christian edu\ncation.\nJewel Givens, Duluth, recent\nly passed thru Mpls. on his way\nto K. C. to visit his sister. He\nwas in the army 34 qjonths and\nrecently stationed in Italy hav\ning been discharged Aug. 11.\nOffirer* CrltlclNed\nWhen SafecraekerN\nENeape\nPatrolmen Joseph Hudak and\nAudrey Doughty operating in\nplain cothes in a private car on\na special detail to prevent safe\njobs noted a screen off of a win\ndow at 206 Colfax Ave. No. Up\non investigating they heard\nwhat was apparently safe crack\ni ers at work and both left the\nscene to secure help. When they\ni returned the robbers had made\ni their escape. The police author\nities promised an investigation\nto determine if negligence on the\npart of the officers contributed\nto the escape of the safecrack-\nI ers.\nSafe men operating in the city\nhave committed about thirty\njobs in the last two months.\nHonor Graduate\nRev. John W. Colburn of En\nnis, Tex., completed his work at\nBishop College. Marshall, Texas,\nin the field of Social Science\nbearing the honor of Magna\nCum Laude.\nGirls\u2019 Friendly Society\nWants New Members\nII you are a young lady la-tween\nI flu* ago* of and II Uh Clrla Fi l\u00bb ml\nIly Society of St Philip a Epln< opal\nchurch Is M 4 king you as a new mem\n\nIhe alm of tlu* organization Is to\nh< ip girls to build souikl Immllch. al\u00ab lt\nmliolK, and spiritual strength.\nI be hum tings are h\u00ab Id every Hatur\n<Jny from II am to 1 pm In the\nI mien roft of Ht Philip s Episcopal\n<hunh,